I spent days studying Solidity security.
Reentrancy. Flash loans. MEV. Proxy patterns.
Then I started looking at AI agents — and realised I'd been studying the wrong half of the problem.
Here's the distinction that changed how I think about both.
𝗟𝗟𝗠 = The Thinker
→ Answers one prompt at a time
→ Stateless. Forgets after each reply.
→ Cannot use tools or APIs on its own
→ Output is text. You still have to act on it.

𝗔𝗜 𝗔𝗴𝗲𝗻𝘁 = The Doer
→ Works toward a goal across many steps
→ Has memory — short term and long term
→ Calls APIs, reads data, triggers real actions
→ Acts between steps without waiting to be asked

The simplest way I can put it:
An LLM tells you a position is undercollateralised.
An agent triggers the liquidation.
An LLM explains how to execute a swap.
An agent executes the swap.
That single word — executes — is where everything changes.
And for us as blockchain developers, it raises an uncomfortable question.
If an agent can execute on-chain actions autonomously — sign transactions, move funds, interact with protocols — what controls it?
A private key gives it everything. No limits. No rules.
That's not an AI problem. That's a smart contract problem. And we already know how to solve it.
